{"query": "How effective are conservation actions such as legal protection, habitat creation, and translocation for great crested newt populations in the UK?", "summary": "Research on conservation actions for great crested newts in the UK shows mixed effectiveness. For translocation, studies found that four of six documented translocations maintained or established breeding populations, with newts present one year after release in 37% of cases. However, breeding failed in 48% of ponds within three years, and a systematic review found no conclusive evidence that translocation resulted in self-sustaining populations. Great crested newts reproduced following 56% of translocations, though some projects also included habitat management or head-started larvae release.

Habitat creation through pond construction showed more positive results. Studies found that naturally colonizing and translocated great crested newts established breeding populations at 57-75% of created ponds. Up to 88% of created ponds were colonized by translocated or naturally colonizing newts, with head-started newts reproducing in 38% of created ponds. However, similar to translocation, a systematic review found no conclusive evidence that mitigation including pond creation resulted in self-sustaining populations.

Regarding legal protection, evidence indicates significant limitations. Three reviews found that legal protection was not effective at protecting amphibian populations during development. While over 600 great crested newt mitigation licenses were issued over 10 years in England and Wales, this increase in licensing did not translate to effective population protection. Additional habitat management actions like creating refugia and artificial hibernacula showed some success, with one study maintaining four great crested newt populations through refuge creation combined with other interventions.", "action_ids": ["858", "863", "779", "860", "867", "772", "759", "785"]}

